04470nam a22005175i 9780300239102DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002391027 a10.12987/97803002391022doi  a(DE-B1597)625791  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aQL737.C25bA94 1997eb 7aNAT0370002bisacsh04a333.95/9766292231 aClark, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAverting Extinction :bReconstructing Endangered Species Recovery /cSusan Clark. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I The Ferret Program and Its Behavior -- tIntroduction -- t1 Black-Footed Ferrets: From Near Extinction to Near Recovery -- t2 Participants and Perspectives: Complexity of Joint Action -- t3 Intelligence Failures and Delays: Two Program Pathologies -- t4 Program Structure as Political Process: Designing for Control -- t5 Goals, Power, and Conflict: Making Decisions -- t6 Advisory Teams, Coordinators, and Field Teams: Legitimizing and Bureaucratizing -- t7 Organizational Learning: Institutionalizing Ignorance -- t8 Problem Definition: Analytical Framework, Process, and Outcome -- tPart II Reconstructing Endangered Species Recovery -- tIntroduction -- t9 Species Recovery as Policy Process: Shifting the Perspective -- t10 New Organizational Arrangements: Processing Information for Effectiveness -- t11 Civic Professionalism: Meeting Society's Needs -- t12 Conclusions -- tEpilogue -- tLiterature Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe black-footed ferret, once thought extinct, was rediscovered in Wyoming in 1981. In this book, Susan Clark tells the story of subsequent efforts to save the black-footed ferret, showing how it points up the necessity of finding new ways to conserve and restore species. According to Clark, the problems facing conservation are not fundamentally biological but stem from human systems-policy decisions, organizational priorities, and professional rivalries. The focus in conservation, he says, must shift from science to practical problem solving.Clark first describes and analyzes efforts to restore the black-footed ferret after 1981 and looks at the processes, people, institutions, and programs that were involved in that endeavor. Finding that the ferret case illustrates many things that go wrong in the implementation of complex environmental policy, Clark then proposes fresh approaches to endangered species recovery. She gives guidelines for improving decision making and development of policies; for devising organizational strategies and structures that are more conducive to learning; and for a new civic professionalism that will raise the standards for performance and better meet society`s needs. This policy-oriented approach, he contends, will open up new avenues, methods, and hope for species recovery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBlack-footed ferretzWyoming. 0aEndangered speciesxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aWildlife recoveryxGovernment policyzUnited States. 7aNATURE / Animals / Wildlife.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300239102?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300239102423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300239102/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles